ce:section.ce:para:
DSC analysis reveals a similar temperature of MgH2 decomposition compared to those determined by TG (Fig. 5
). The dehydriding of the alloys show a two peak endothermic effect. Whereas for the alloy with Mn the two peaks are separated, for the other two alloys they are overlapped. As it was already mentioned the presence of the low (β-MgH2) and high (γ-MgH2) temperature MgH2 was detected in the three alloys by XRD, but the amount of the β-MgH2 is essentially higher. Therefore, the two-peak endothermic effect cannot be explained only with the two MgH2 phases formed during RMM and has to be further clarified. The enthalpy of dehydriding of the Mg alloys with different alloying elements was determined from the DSC curves. Assigning this enthalpy to the amount of the hydride in the alloys (determined by TG) the enthalpies of the hydride decomposition were obtained. The lowest value, 56kJ/mol H2, corresponds to dehydriding of Mg87Ni3Al3Mn7–H, which is substantially lower than the value for the pure MgH2 (75kJ/mol H2) and is close to that determined recently for a similar alloy Mg87Ni3Al7Mn3
[10]. The alloy with Mm shows the highest enthalpy of dehydriding, ∼70kJ/mol.
